title.narrative: Provision of Non-Food Items (NFI) and Lifesaving Shelter Assistance to Earthquake-Affected Households in Türkiye

description.narrative:
The earthquake response in Türkiye is being lead and coordinated by the Disaster and Emergency Management Authority. A three-month state of emergency has been declared for eleven provinces that were directly affected by the earthquake. Around 3 million people, including migrants, are displaced in various settings including those choosing to stay close to their homes and others moving further away from their usual residence. An estimated 1.7 million people live in informal settlements, mostly in makeshift shelters or tents with extremely basic living conditions. Some of these settlements lack proper water and sanitation services and also require immediate assistance with basic household items and shelter support.
In response to the immediate need for better shelter and access to basic services, the International Organization for Migration (IOM) is improving access to basic services and temporary living conditions for populations affected by environmental hazards through the procurement and delivery of tents, living containers and essential housing items.

title.narrative: Emergency Grant Aid in Response to the Earthquake in Türkiye and Syria

description.narrative: An earthquake of 7.7 magnitude with the epicentre in the south-east of the country, struck Türkiye on 6 February 2023 at 04:17 AM. Another earthquake of 7.65 magnitude occurred at 13:24 PM on the same day. Over 2,700 aftershocks have been registered in the region so far. The earthquakes came at the peak of the winter season and are considered the largest earthquakes for centuries in the region. A three-month state of emergency has been declared for ten provinces directly affected by the earthquake. The Turkish government is leading the response through coordination by the Disaster and Emergency Management Authority (AFAD). IOM, through this project, is contributing to addressing lifesaving humanitarian needs of earthquake-affected populations in Türkiye through the procurement and transportation of improved shelter units and mobile latrines.

title.narrative: Lifesaving Emergency Assistance for Disaster-Affected Populations in Türkiye​​

description.narrative:
Two earthquakes with a magnitude of 7.7 and 7.65 respectively struck Turkiye on 7 February 2023. As of 27 February, 44,374 people have lost their lives and 164,321 buildings have collapsed or are heavily damaged. There is an urgent need to provide shelter and non-food items (NFIs) to affected individuals, particularly as 1.9 million people are living in tents or temporary shelters. Thousands of people are without safe drinking water and sanitation facilities such as running water and toilets. In these conditions there is a risk of a waterborne disease outbreak. Moreover, earthquake-affected populations are exposed to compounded protection risks. Affected individuals are in need of comprehensive protection services to address ongoing vulnerabilities and preclude negative coping mechanisms.
Through this project, the International Organization for Migration (IOM) is contributing to efforts to save lives and alleviate suffering in the aftermath of the earthquakes that struck Türkiye through a multi-sectoral response, including a community-based approach to addressing the most urgent protection needs of affected populations as well as the provision of hygiene kits and items, tents and NFIs, and the deployment of the Displacement Tracking Matrix in selected sites to capture needs and inform humanitarian interventions.

sector.narrative: Movement, Emergency and Post-Crisis Migration Management

title.narrative: Emergency Lifesaving NFI, Tent and Protection Support to Earthquake-Affected Populations in Türkiye

description.narrative: According to the latest statement made by Türkiye’s Disaster and Emergency Management Presidency (AFAD), as of 11 February 2023, a total of 20,665 individuals have lost their lives and 80,088 individuals were rescued after two major earthquakes and numerous aftershocks struck the region. These numbers are expected to increase further over the coming days/weeks due to prevailing cold weather conditions and the fact that some disaster zone areas have not yet been reached by search and rescue teams. In both affected and hosting areas, affected populations are in urgent need of Non-Food Items (NFI), including blankets, mattresses, and winter-resistant tents. Whilst local municipalities and AFAD are assessing infrastructures and residential buildings to ascertain their damages and safety levels, the need for more immediate shelter solutions will remain, as well as a need for winterization NFI assistance. This projects’ overall objective is to provide humanitarian assistance and protection services in Türkiye to save lives and respond to immediate humanitarian needs. The delivery of targeted lifesaving assistance is ensured through the procurement, transportation, and distribution of: (i) NFIs and (ii) winterization shelter support, as well as the (iii) provision of critical protection monitoring and support to earthquake-affected populations.

title.narrative: Information for Refugees, Asylum-seekers and Stateless People

description.narrative:
In the early morning of Monday the 6th of February, a major earthquake of magnitude 7.8, on the Richter scale hit southern Turkey and northwestern Syria. The earthquake caused a large number of casualties and widespread destruction to infrastructure and civilian buildings in both southern Turkey and Northern Syria. Just a few hours later, in the afternoon, a second earthquake of 7.5 magnitude was recorded, whose epicenter was also in southern Turkey. In addition, dozens of aftershocks of lesser intensity followed the initial earthquake and further damage is expected in the coming days.

This major humanitarian disaster calls for immediate action. All partners have presence on the ground and can scale up their response immediately. In light of the current crisis, we initiated the Acute Crisis Mechanism. This proposal focuses on multiple sectors.

description.narrative: On the 6th of February at close to 4:17 am, a 7.8 degrees magnitude earthquake struck southern Turkey near Syria’s northern border. The US Geological Survey said the earthquake was centered about 33 km (20 miles) from Gaziantep, a major city and provincial capital. Tremors were felt as far away as Lebanon, Greece, Palestine and the island of Cyprus. Another big earthquake was felt on the same day at around 1:24 pm local time, largely in the same affected areas.

The strategy of the IFRC response will be to contribute to support 300,000 affected people in the affected areas for a period of 11 months. Targeting will prioritize the most vulnerable groups such as separated families, female-headed households, children, people with disabilities and the elderly among other groups of special needs.

Through this Emergency Appeal, the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies (IFRC) together with the partner national societies aim to support the Syrian Arab Red Crescent Society in the response to this Syria Earthquake.
